abstract: ATLANTA, Dec. 3--Although mayors attending the National League of Cities convention here appear resigned to the prospect of some deep cuts in Federal assistance, even the most conservative ones say that an array of urban programs may be politically immune to elimination or drastic cuts under the incoming Reagan administration.
headline_main: Mayors See Hope on Reagan Programs; Urban Development Grants Promise on Bloc Programs League Becomes Lobby
headline_print_headline: Mayors See Hope on Reagan Programs; Urban Development Grants Promise on Bloc Programs League Becomes Lobby
byline_original: By John Herbers Special To the New York Times

abstract: WASHINGTON, Dec. 2--Presidentelect Ronald Reagan, drawing on both the Eastern establishment and his West Coast political associates, has decided on the four men he wants to form the inner ring of his Cabinet, well-placed Republican sources said today.
headline_main: 4 REPORTED CHOSEN AS THE INNER CIRCLE OF REAGAN CABINET; Haig at State Dept.; Weinberger at Defense; Wriston at Treasury; Smith, Attorney General Caution on Clearances Casey and Stockman Listed 4 REPORTED CHOSEN FOR REAGAN CABINET Possible Agriculture Choice Blend of Old and New

abstract: OAKLAND, Calif., Dec. 2--In the aftermath of an unusual evening at the Oakland-Alameda County Coliseum, in which a demonstration by almost everyone in a crowd of 51,583 upstaged the football game, Al Davis accused Pete Rozelle, the commissioner of the National Football League, of "undermining" his team.
headline_main: Davis Faults Rozelle For Raiders' Trouble; No Comment From Rozelle Cheerleaders No Help
headline_print_headline: Davis Faults Rozelle For Raiders' Trouble; No Comment From Rozelle Cheerleaders No Help
byline_original: By William N. Wallace Special To the New York Times

abstract: The National Football League ruled yesterday that Walter Payton of the Chicago Bears did not lose control of the ball and fumble in a controversial play during a game on Nov. 23 that the Atlanta Falcons won, 28-17.

headline_main: Striking a Balance on Rent Control
headline_print_headline: Striking a Balance on Rent Control

abstract: AT KANSAS CITY, Mo.--The Bengals, breaking a five-game losing streak, held the Chiefs without a touchdown for the first time in 13 games this season. Kansas City (6-7) scored on field goals of 26 and 40 yards by Nick Lowery.
